content.title: Document Content
content.visibleText:
Competitor Deep Dive - Digital SAT

All providers offer 1-to-1 tutoring online or over e-mail in at least one of their packages. The price for 1-to-1 tutoring ranges from $50-$75/hour. The availability of 1-to-1 or private tutoring can be seen as a core value driver for parents â€“ this is because it is considered one of the most premium, desirable, and helpful forms of academic support.

6. All providers have a limited number of practice tests, and a limited number of practice questions.
All providers have a limited practice test question bank (4-6 tests) and a limited practice question bank (1,500-4,000 questions or 40-100 per skill/standard).

7. All paid providers provide a score guarantee, with some offering an additional satisfaction guarantee.
Almost all providers offer a score and/or satisfaction guarantee (link). Most providers offer a score guarantee of between 100 and 180 points. Kaplan stands out in this regard, only offering a +1 pt or 'higher score' guarantee.

8. All providers offer the option to finance purchases.

9. No providers make mention of leveraging AI within their offerings. This could be an opportunity to differentiate.

10. All providers make it clear that their content has been updated for the Digital SAT, and all of their content is framed in a way that is applicable to both parents and students.
All of the SAT Prep websites are framed in a manner such that the content is applicable to both students and parents. Additionally, it is important to note that all websites make it clear that their content has been updated for the Digital SAT. Ongoing demands from tutors, YouTube SAT program reviewers, students, and parents suggest to other providers that they are paying for does not contain traditional or old-style SAT questions. Some programs do not make this clear, and students and influencers suggest to each other to clear to avoid.

11. Only PrepScholar discloses their average student SAT score point increases.
PrepScholar's average score increase is 180 pts, with 1,230 score start to a 1410 score end. They also note that the top 25% of students improved their SAT score by 370 pts.

12. Some vendors, like PrepExpert offer 'family pass' whereby all students in a household get access. TeachTap should consider doing the same.
Unlike APs which are mainly taken in 11th and 12th grade, many high performing students begin studying for the SAT in the 9th or 10th grade. This widens the scope and makes it much more likely that a given family/household with more than 1 student in high school likely also has another child in high school. This is compatible with the GTM strategy of targeting grandparents.
